Note¶

The percentage of budget so far is not shown in the following data.Therefore, we will try to calculate the budget percentage of Total the project budget by:

  • Calculate total budget hours for each project.
  • Calculation Divide the budget for each Milestone by the total budget hours for each project.

    %Budget = Budget Hours / Total Budget Hours

In [25]:
Project_TotalBudget=Hours_df.groupby(['Project Code'])['Budget Hours'].sum().sort_values().reset_index()
In [26]:
Hours_df=Hours_df.merge(Project_TotalBudget, left_on='Project Code', right_on='Project Code')
Hours_df.rename(columns = {'Budget Hours_y':'Total Budget Hours','Budget Hours_x':'Budget Hours'}, inplace = True)
In [27]:
Hours_df['%Budget']=Hours_df['Budget Hours']/Hours_df['Total Budget Hours']

Hours_df['WeekNum_ProjectWeek']=Hours_df['Week'].str[-2:]

Hours_df['Planned % Complete']=Hours_df['WeekNum_ProjectWeek'].astype(int)/Hours_df['WeekNum_Period_To'].astype(int)

Budget vs Actual vs Forecast Cost¶

The key difference between a budget and a forecast is that a budget lays out the plan for what a business wants to achieve, while a forecast states its actual expectations for results, usually in a much more summarized format

  • Budget: What your startup expects to achieve
  • Actuals: What your startup actually achieved
  • Forecast: What your startup is projected to achieve in the future based on past data

where

  • Estimated cost = budgeted cost of work completed (Forecasted Hours * Cost Rate);
  • Actual Cost = actual expenses incurred (Hours * Cost Rate)
  • Planning Cost = actual expenses incurred (Budget Hours * Cost Rate)
  • Total Budget cost = actual expenses incurred (Total Budget Hours * Cost Rate)
In [29]:
Hours_df['Actual Cost'] = Hours_df['Hours'] * Hours_df['Cost Rate']
Hours_df['Budget cost']  = Hours_df['Budget Hours'] * Hours_df['Cost Rate']
Hours_df['Total Budget cost']  = Hours_df['Total Budget Hours'] * Hours_df['Cost Rate']
Hours_df['Estimated cost']  = Hours_df['Forecasted hours'] * Hours_df['Cost Rate']

Planned Value (PV), Earned Value (EV) in Project Cost Management¶

Planned Value (PV)

  • This is the first element of earned value management. Planned Value is the approved value of the work to be completed in a given time. It is the value that you should have earned as per the schedule.
  • Planned Value = (Planned % Complete) X (Total Budget cost)

Earned Value (EV)

  • Earned Value is the value of the work actually completed to date. If the project is terminated today, Earned Value will show you the value that the project has produced.

  • Earned Value = % of completed work (%Budget) X BAC (Total Budget cost).

In [30]:
Hours_df['Planned Value'] = Hours_df['Planned % Complete'] * Hours_df['Total Budget Hours']* Hours_df['Cost Rate']
Hours_df['Earned Value'] = Hours_df['%Budget'] * Hours_df['Total Budget Hours'] * Hours_df['Cost Rate']

Schedule Performance Index (KPI)¶

The schedule performance index (SPI) is a tracking metric used to measure completion progress against the schedule. It eliminates guesswork and allows the project manager to provide timely improvements to increase resource efficiency. The SPI is a ratio of the planned value to the actual value and is calculated as:

SPI = Earned value (EV) / Planned value (PV)

In [31]:
Hours_df['SPI']=Hours_df['Earned Value']/Hours_df['Planned Value']

Cost Performance Index (KPI)¶

The cost performance index (CPI) measures financial management efficiency in a project. CPI ratios have the following implications:

  • The project is said to have underperformed when CPI was less than 1.
  • A CPI greater than one means that performance was better than expected.
  • Performance was on target if CPI was equal to 1.

CPI fluctuates throughout a projects lifespan because of variable expenses like wages and prices of inputs. Using CPI metrics, project managers can make decisions that influence the delivery of projects within the budget.

CPI = Earned value (EV) / Actual costs (AC)

In [32]:
Hours_df['CPI']=Hours_df['Earned Value']/Hours_df['Actual Cost']

Budget Variance (KPI)¶

Budget variance is done to measure the difference between the estimated expenses (Budget Cost) and Actual Cost. Also known as cost variance (CV), it is used to track expense items within project activities, helping the manager decide how best to allocate the remaining resources for optimal performance. BV outcomes can be summarized as:

  • Positive = below budget
  • Zero = within budget
  • Negative = exceeds the budget

Budget variance = Budget value Actual value (AV)

In [33]:
Hours_df['Budget Variance'] = Hours_df['Earned Value'] - Hours_df['Actual Cost']

Detect outlier¶

In [54]:
def outlier(df_in, col_name):
    q1 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1 #Interquartile range
    fence_low  = q1-1.5*iqr
    fence_high = q3+1.5*iqr
    df_out = df_in.loc[~(df_in[col_name] > fence_low) & (df_in[col_name] < fence_high)]
    return df_out

Despite the differences in characteristics, it appears that the proportions are equal and the patterns are consistent.¶

In [71]:
def is_outlier(points, thresh=3.5):
    if len(points.shape) == 1:
        points = points[:,None]
    median = np.median(points, axis=0)
    diff = np.sum((points - median)**2, axis=-1)
    diff = np.sqrt(diff)
    med_abs_deviation = np.median(diff)

    modified_z_score = 0.6745 * diff / med_abs_deviation

    return modified_z_score > thresh
